    <Folder>
      <name>Intelligence Summary</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>AI Council Assessment</name>
        <styleUrl>#intel</styleUrl>
        <description>The tracking data reveals a globally distributed U.S. military posture with concentrated air activity in CONUS training areas and sustained naval operations across multiple theaters. Strategic airlift platforms (C-17, C-30J) are frequently observed in high-altitude transit, indicating ongoing rotational deployments between theaters, particularly supporting Pacific pivot operations and regional security cooperation. Training sorties dominate CONUS activity, with T-38 Talons in Oklahoma and PC-21s in Australia suggesting expanded pilot training pipelines, including foreign military sales programs. Naval deployments reflect a multi-theater strategy: USS Gerald R. Ford CSG operates in the Caribbean following Middle East redeployment, while USS George Washington conducts operations in the Philippine Sea, demonstrating sustained Pacific presence. The USS Thomas Hudner&#39;s deployment to the Arabian Sea aligns with heightened regional tensions, and USS Makin Island&#39;s presence near Japan underscores amphibious readiness. ISR activity is evident through P-8 Poseidon and Beechcraft King Air missions, though limited position data constrains full situational awareness. Unusual patterns include the high frequency of MH-60 Sea Hawk patrols off San Diego and the presence of Marine Corps helicopters in inland CONUS, likely supporting homeland security or training missions. The overall posture reflects a globally responsive force with emphasis on rapid deployment capabilities, multi-domain operations, and sustained deterrence across the Pacific and Middle East theaters. The absence of detailed positional data for several high-interest platforms (e.g., P-8s) remains a critical gap in assessing full operational coverage.</description>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>0,0,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
    </Folder>
